The jovial Bardo who love the Muse The Muses’ number ne'er refuse, While the sweet Graues who abhor The strife of oups und wordy war, Lest wine and friendship disagree Contine their votaries to three.

But frenzy fires me now-the bowl Works its full influenoe on my soul; Why sleeps the Berecynthian flute? Why ore the pipe's shrill breothings mute? Why hange the lyre upon the wall?

Ι hate a thrifty festival.

Then soatter roses on your bruun, Let Lycus with his ill-matohed sponse

, The aged Lycus hear our joy, And wish himself again a boy. To thee all bright with flowing hair And beaming like young Hesper’s star The willing Rhode gives her charms, Me Glycera’s fair image warnis.
